explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER - macro that may perform an early return, longjmp or abort on a NULL timer_id; its expansion determines whether code after the check can be unreachable.

OS_CHECK_APINAME - macro that may perform an early return, longjmp or abort on a bad timebase_name; its expansion determines reachability of the subsequent code.

OS_TaskGetId_Impl - returns the current task/context id passed to OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl; its behavior in timer-callback context is required to know which object type can be produced.

OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl - maps an object id to an object type; needed to determine whether the if-condition (objtype == OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE) can be true or false (i.e., whether either branch is reachable).

OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE - the constant compared against objtype; its value/meaning is needed to reason about possible return values from OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl and therefore branch reachability.

OS_ObjectIdFindByName - the function called after the conditional return; required to determine whether that call (and subsequent return) can actually be reached in any execution path.

OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE - the return value used in the conditional branch; needed to confirm that the branch performs a return (making code after it unreachable on that path).

osal_objtype_t - the type of objtype; its definition (enumeration) lists possible object types and is required to reason about possible values and thus branch feasibility.

osal_id_t - the type of timer_id parameter; its semantics (e.g., special values) may influence check macros or ObjectId functions and thereby affect reachability.

int32 - return type definition (and any associated macros/constants for return codes) to understand possible return-value semantics used by the checks and called functions.

Note: If OS_CHECK_POINTER or OS_CHECK_APINAME expand to calls that themselves can abort/never return (or invoke test stubs that do), include those called symbols as well when doing the detailed reachability proof.
